DESCRIPTION_columns: Date at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC).   E.g. "25-Jun-2009"
DESCRIPTION_format: "Date at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC). E.g. '25-Jun-2009'"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Time at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC).  E.g. “19:35:37.440”.  Note that leapseconds allow a second to be of value 60, e.g. “19:35:60.440”.
DESCRIPTION_format: "Time at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC). E.g. '19:35.37.440'"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Julian Date at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC). E.g. 2454102.123456789
DESCRIPTION_format: "Julian Date at the midpoint of observation (SCET, UTC). E.g. 2454102.123456789"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Orbit number.  0 to 99999
DESCRIPTION_format: "Orbit number. 0 to 99999"

DESCRIPTION_columns: The distance from the center of the moon to the sun (AU).  E.g. 1.00001
DESCRIPTION_format: "The distance from the center of the moon to the sun (AU). E.g. 1.00001"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Subsolar Latitude (deg).  -1.7 to 1.7 degrees.
DESCRIPTION_format: "Subsolar Latitude (deg). E.g. -1.54333"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Subsolar East Longitude (deg). 0.00000 to 360.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Subsolar East Longitude (deg). 0.00000 to 360.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Spacecraft clock at midpoint of observation (seconds.subseconds).   The seconds are relative to the 2001 epoch.   The numbers to the right of the decimal point are not decimal fraction of a second but rather subseconds.  Each second is divided into 65536 subseconds, thus the range for subseconds is 0 – 65535.    Example:  123456789.00001
DESCRIPTION_format: "Spacecraft clock at midpoint of observation (seconds.subseconds).  The seconds are relative to the 2001 epoch.  The numbers to the right of the decimal point are not decimal fraction of a second but rather subseconds.  Each second is divided into 65536 subseconds, thus the range for subseconds is 0 - 65535. Example: 123456789.00001"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Subspacecraft Latitude (deg).  -90.00000 to 90.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Subspacecraft Latitude (deg). -90.00000 to 90.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Subspacecraft East Longitude (deg).  0 to 360.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Subspacecraft East Longitude (deg). 0 to 360.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Distance from the center of moon to the spacecraft (km).   E.g.: 11000.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Distance from the center of moon to the spacecraft (km). E.g.: 11000.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Distance from the surface of the moon to the spacecraft (km).  E.g.: 11000.00000.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS.
DESCRIPTION_format: "Distance from the surface of the moon to the spacecraft (km). E.g.: 11000.00000.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS."

DESCRIPTION_columns: Last Elevation Command (deg).  0 to 270.000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Last Elevation Command (deg). 0 to 270.000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Last Azimuth Command (deg). 0 to 270.000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Last Azimuth Command (deg). 0 to 270.000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Activity Flag.  Range is -999 to 999.  See Appendix B of DLRE RDR SIS for description
DESCRIPTION_format: "Activity Flag. See Appendix B of DLRE RDR SIS for description"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Orientation Latitude (deg).  The latitudinal component of the "orientation vector",  a vector from the center of the moon in the direction of the detector array direction  (defined as from detector 21 to detector 1).  Provides angular orientation of the FOV's.  -90.00000 to 90.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Orientation Latitude (deg). The latitudinal component of the 'orientation vector',  a vector from the center of the moon in the direction of the detector array direction  (defined as from detector 21 to detector 1).  Provides angular orientation of the FOV's. -90.00000 to 90.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Orientation Longitude (deg).  The east longitudinal component of the "orientation vector",  a vector from the center of the moon in the direction of the detector array direction  (defined as from detector 21 to detector 1).  Provides angular orientation of the FOV's.  0 to 360.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Orientation Longitude (deg). The east longitudinal component of the 'orientation vector',  a vector from the center of the moon in the direction of the detector array direction  (defined as from detector 21 to detector 1).  Provides angular orientation of the FOV's. 0 to 360.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Diviner Channel Number. 1 to 9
DESCRIPTION_format: "Diviner Channel Number. 1 to 9"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Diviner Detector Number. 1 to 21
DESCRIPTION_format: "Diviner Detector Number. 1 to 21"

DESCRIPTION_columns: The X component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS. Range -1.0 to 1.0, e.g. -0.999999
DESCRIPTION_format: "The X component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. E.g. -0.999999"

DESCRIPTION_columns: The Y component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS. Range -1.0 to 1.0, e.g. -0.999999
DESCRIPTION_format: "The Y component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. E.g. -0.999999"

DESCRIPTION_columns: The Z component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS. Range -1.0 to 1.0, e.g. -0.999999
DESCRIPTION_format: "The Z component of the Diviner Look Unit Vector, using the lunar coordinate system  described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. E.g. -0.999999"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Calibrated Radiance (W m**-2 sr**-1).  The realistic range of radiance is -1000.0000 to 1000.0000  (This text was not in rdr_formats.txt file: “but this number can be as high as  99999.9999 during spacecraft or instrument anomalies.”)
DESCRIPTION_format: "Calibrated Radiance (W m**-2 sr**-1). Range is -1000.0000 to 1000.0000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Calibrated Brightness Temperature (K).   Except for Channels 1 and 2, which is radiance  relative to normally illuminated Lambert surface at sun-moon distance.  The realistic range of tb is -450.000 to 450.000, but this number can be as high as  9999.999 during spacecraft or instrument anomalies.  Negative values correspond to negative radiances.
DESCRIPTION_format: "Calibrated Brightness Temperature (K). Except for Channels 1 and 2, which is radiance  relative to normally illuminated Lambert surface at sun-moon distance.  Range is -450.000 to 450.000, where negative tb values correspond to negative radiance values."

DESCRIPTION_columns: Latitude of FOV center (deg).  Undefined if off planet.  Uses spherical moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS.  Range is -90.00000 to 90.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Latitude of FOV center (deg). Undefined if off planet. Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation  as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. -90.00000 to 90.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: East longitude of FOV center (deg).  Undefined if off planet.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS.  0 to 360.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "East longitude of FOV center (deg). Undefined if off planet. Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation  as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. 0 to 360.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Emission Angle at FOV center (deg).   This is the angle between the vector from the surface FOV center to Diviner and a “normal” vector drawn perpendicular to the Moon’s surface.  Undefined if off planet. Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3.  0 to 90.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Emission Angle at FOV center (deg). Undefined if off planet. Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation  as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. 0 to 90.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Solar Zenith angle at FOV center (deg). This is the angle between the vector from the surface  FOV center to the Sun and a "normal" vector drawn perpendicular to the Moon's surface.  Undefined when off planet except during solar calibrations when it is defined as the angle  between the vector to the Sun and the normal vector of the solar calibration target.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS. 0 to 180.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Solar Zenith angle at FOV center (deg). Undefined when off planet except during solar calibrations  when it is defined as the solar zenith angle of the detector FOV center projected onto  the solar calibration target.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. 0 to 180.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Solar Azimuth Angle at FOV Center (deg).  0 degrees when aligned with the solar vector and  measured counter-clockwise when looking down at the planet.  Undefined when off planet except  during solar calibrations when it is defined as the angle between the projection of the vector to the  sun onto the solar calibration target plane and the X-axis of the solar calibration target reference system (STS) .  The X-axis direction of the STS is roughly parallel to the outward edge of the solar calibration target panel.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS. Range is  0 to 360.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Solar Azimuth Angle at FOV Center (deg). 0 degrees when aligned with the solar vector and  measured counter-clockwise when looking down at the planet.  Undefined when off planet except during solar calibrations when it is defined as the solar  azimuth angle of the detector FOV center projected onto the solar calibration target.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. 0 to 360.00000"

DESCRIPTION_columns: Local time at FOV Center (hours past midnight).   Undefined if off planet.  Uses spherical moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3. of the RDR SIS.  Range is  0 to 24.00000
DESCRIPTION_format: "Local time at FOV Center (hours past midnight). Undefined if off planet.  Uses ellipsoidal moon approximation as described in Section 2.4.3 of the RDR SIS. 0 to 24.00000"

"Quality Flag for Calibration. A 3-digit decimal integer representing an 8-bit binary quality flag.  Bits set to 1 represent various conditions which compromise data quality.  A value of zero represents best quality and increasing values indicate lower quality.  Range is 0 to 255. See Appendix C of the RDR SIS for more details."

"Quality Flag for Geometry. A 3-digit decimal integer representing an 8-bit binary quality flag.  Bits set to 1 represent various conditions which compromise data quality.  A value of zero represents best quality and increasing values indicate lower quality.  Range is 0 to 255. See Appendix C of the RDR SIS for more details."
